<paragraph blockId="104.[189,457,702,728]" box="[189,457,702,728]" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,457,702,728]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,457,702,728]" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="104.[189,1399,750,960]" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">
Moderately large, mostly yellowish orange and white-faced; differentiated from all other species by the combination of the white orbits, the narrow clypeus, the transverse head, the absence of a femoral tooth and the short ovipositor. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rousse, Villemant &amp; Seyrig" authorityYear="2013" box="[555,791,823,849]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Pristomerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vahaza">
<emphasis box="[555,791,823,849]" italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Pristomerus vahaza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be related to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morley" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[1087,1231,823,849]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Pristomerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albescens">
<emphasis box="[1087,1231,823,849]" italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">P. albescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with which it shares the unusually transverse head and narrow clypeus, but these species cannot be confused because 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Morley" baseAuthorityYear="1917" box="[189,336,897,923]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Pristomerus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albescens">
<emphasis box="[189,336,897,923]" italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">P. albescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has an apically straight ovipositor, a strongly reduced but distinct femoral tooth and a distinctly darker head.
</paragraph>
